devastating: 72% of men prefer women to stay at home while also disagreeing with women who believe it’s their right to work.

In addition, only 26% of men in Lebanon think that women should be able to decide to terminate their pregnancy.

Timeline: Facts and figures on women’s rights in the Middle East

The research was conducted among 5,000 men and women in 12 countries across the Middle East and North Africa by UN Women, the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women. The study included a 1,000-person sample of men and women from Lebanon.

According to Azza Karam, who co-authored the State of the World’s Fathers report, in 89 percent of the 12 countries represented in the study, men disapprove of women having jobs or working.

Meanwhile, Egypt topped the list of countries with the highest rate (80 percent) of men believing it was a woman’s place to be at home.

Saudis have the most traditional beliefs, even though it’s the only country represented to have female ministers, according to Karam.

Half of Lebanese men questioned said that the husband should be able to divorce his wife, with 46 percent thinking they should decide who to chat with. A third of both men and women in Lebanon said that a man has the right to beat his wife, and 75 percent of women said it was acceptable to deny divorce to their husband if they want it.
